Ensuring Accessible Interactions

02
On this page
  1. Notes on Interactivity
  2. Affordances in Interaction Design

Notes on Interactivity

Often, accessible interactivity can fall flat from a design perspective. The following concepts and resources will provide you with tips to approach interactivity with accessibility in mind:

Anything mouse users can do, keyboard and Assistive Technology users must also. This means thinking about access without a mouse. How will it work? Can the same action be completed with a keyboard or will it make more sense to add a button or other control for keyboard and screen reader access?

Make interactive controls obvious. This is in the realm of the classic book, Don’t Make Me Think! Users should be able to tell visually which elements are interactive without having to hover, focus, or touch them to find out. This reduces the cognitive burden of learning a user interface and makes it more intuitive to use.

Keyboard focus indicators must be visible. This supports the previous two items in making keyboard-accessible user interfaces. Users need to be able to see their focus point on the screen for an interaction to be accessible.

Use a minimum target size of 24 x 24 pixels. By using adequate target size, people can more easily click and touch user interface controls. Sometimes, it’s as simple as adding more padding to a link or icon button to provide adequate space. This success criterion is under discussion for WCAG version 2.2, level AA.

Beware changes of context on focus or input. Resist creating interfaces that expand to show additional controls on focus or move/navigate the user upon typing in an input or making a form selection. Also note that a change in content is not the same as a change in context, so it may still be okay to use a native select element to filter or display content on the same page.

Include ways to extend or adjust time limits. Some users need more time to complete tasks before a change in context like a time out or page refresh. Depending on the use case, you may need to provide a mechanism to turn off, adjust, or extend a time limit in the interface.

Content shown on hover or focus must be dismissible and persistent. This mostly applies to patterns like tooltips, submenus, and non-modal dialogs or popups, to ensure content that was triggered can be easily hidden again.

Some of these items take more learning and study, so I would recommend reading up on them in the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines. At the very least, I would recommend taking “baby steps” like making sure:

  • Interactive controls are keyboard focusable and operable
  • Visible focus indicators are present
  • Interactive touch targets are large enough for human fingers, including people with tremors

Affordances in Interaction Design

An affordance is a term for what a user can do with an object based on their capabilities.

It answers the question: What actions can they take?

We want to ensure we're not designing barriers that users can't operate, including with screen readers and other Assistive Technologies.

When reviewing a design system or giving feedback to a team, accessibility should be thought of early enough that we can produce something that works from the start. But at the very least, we need the ability to influence how it gets designed before committing to an inaccessible implementation.

The earlier you can have that discussion, the better.

Ideally, the design and creative folks in your organization are already thinking about accessible affordances in their processes.

Offering numerous ways to complete a task in your application can be helpful for discovery and usability. The goal is not to create a “separate but equal” experience where people with disabilities are shipped off to an “accessible” but stripped-down experience. Rather, provide intuitive interfaces as a baseline for everyone with enhancements for power users.

An example would be a card pattern with a linked heading to navigate to content by keyboard or screen reader, where the whole card is also clickable for mouse users. There are two affordances for the same action (navigating to an article), depending on the user’s abilities.
